    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Fairness in the Bronx</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Herb Rosenthal letter sees unfairness in trial of police officers in Diallo case, whether proceedings are held in the Bronx or in Albany (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>According to Bob Herbert (column, Dec. 27), the trial in Albany of the four policemen accused in the death of Amadou Diallo will surely result in acquittal. Equally certain is that if the trial were to be held in the Bronx it would end with a guilty verdict. In view of this dilemma, played out time and again, has the jury system lost its relevance in this place at this time? How about trial by fire, or drawing straws?</p>
        <p>HERB ROSENTHAL  Somers, N.Y., Dec. 27, 1999</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
